ReviewText: I'm not an audiophile at all I'm actually hearing impaired approx 50%. I also have small ear canals and most buds hurt like heck or don't even fit properly. I figured after checking reviews go give these a chance. I do have over the ear Sony extra bass wireless but don't always want to use those. I liked the look when I opened the package was nice they are in fact, in my opinion, light weight as some said they were kind of heavy. I tried them with default tips and right away my ears hurt. I opened the pack of tips and got a huge surprise. They have extra small tips......I've never seen extra small tips in my life I mean they are so small I thought they were a joke at first.  I figured well let's go straight to these from what looks like default medium tips.They FIT... They immediately felt comfortable and there was no pain at all. They were snug in the ear and offered decent passive noise cancelling. I am very happy with that. I connected these to my iPhone 15 pro max using apple usbc to 3.5mm audio cable and sound was very nice. Like I mentioned I'm no audiophile but I know what music sounds like to me from cheap earbuds and headphones to my 350 dollar wiress Sony extra bass headphones. I love those for the over the ear. These are the best sounding earbuds I've gotten in a very long time. Now that could be because they actually fit nice or. ust because they actually are just that good. Also first time using an iem so no experience there either. A lot of the time my right ear sounded plugged up. These no problems at all so if you got small ear canals give these a shot with smallest tips.

Product: True Wireless Sleep Earbuds, Damipow Noise Blocking Technology Bluetooth Headphones in-Ear, Smallest and Lightest, Ultra Comfortable Designed Specifically to Help You Asleep Faster and Sleep Better
Date: Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 29 June 2021
ReviewText: Let me be clear, for the price - these are some of the most incredible in-ears I've had the pleasure of listening to. Now, I'm no audiophile, but I am a music lover who knows enough about sound to give a reasonable account of these. For reference, in the past I've owned Shure, Sennheiser, RHA, Bose, Cambridge Audio and more that I can't remember. I DJ (through Sennheiser HD25) so mainly listen to Trance, Techno and House. These are my first foray into 'Chi-Fi' and I think I may have just become addicted.I'm not going to use clich√©d terms like "you'll hear parts of songs you've not heard before", because that's subjective and depends what you're used to listening to your music through. But hands down, and again, for the money, these are some of the most exciting in-ears I've owned.Compared to my daily beaters (Sennhesier Momentum IEM) these are way more forward sounding, have better sound stage, better mids and sound more dynamic and responsive. They honestly blew me away, and when doing some A/B testing with my Sennheisers I almost couldn't believe what I was hearing. These things are ¬£20 and just smashed some ¬£100+ earphones from one of the world's most prominent audio houses into outer space! I almost considered throwing the Sennheisers into the bin!?!They are insanely sensitive and easy to drive. From the audio out on my Windows laptop, vol 20 something is more than loud enough (once we're into the 30s/40s it gets uncomfortable) whereas I had to push my Sennheisers up to 60/70.Now the caveat, and this is down to personal taste more than anything and the music I listen to - they lack a little in the bottom end and I'd like a touch more sub-bass if I was being picky. However, I'd probably get that higher up in the KZ range spending more money on some quad driver IEMs and I may just have to try something like theZS10 or ThieAudio Legacy 2's, which I'm sure will hit a little harder on the low end. I may also try some comply tips for these...If you're not into particularly bass heavy music, and want something exciting to listen to (I'd imagine Jazz would sound great on these) then these have to be on your list. Bottom line; exceptional for the money and most people would be more than happy with these!

ReviewText: Quando si parla di Yamaha per quanto riguarda strumenti musicali e accessori, possiamo stare sicuri di parlare di un prodotto di altissima qualit√†, di un brand di altissima qualit√† e avere un esperienza complessiva altrettanto di qualit√†.Queste Yamaha TW-E7B sono un prodotto con caratteristiche al top ad un prezzo, passatemi il termine, quasi "folle" e un audio senza eguali.Il prodotto arriva in una piccola scatolina in cartone marchiata Yamaha, semplice e con nessuna particolarit√† evidente all'esterno.All'interno oltre alle nostre cuffie comprese di proprio case di ricarica, troviamo anche il cavo Usb type-C per la ricarica e vari gommini per far adattare al meglio le cuffie al proprio orecchio.Parto subito con il dirvi che non sono delle cuffie proprio compatte, infatti sia il case di ricarica che le cuffie stesse risultano veramente grandi rispetto a qualsiasi cuffia bluetooth mai provata, le dimensioni esterne del case sono di ‚Äé6.1 x 3.9 x 4.5 cm , con un peso complessivo di 7.3 grammi.La qualit√† dei materiali √® sublime, plastica ben curata e rifinita di un nero 8nel mio caso) opaco con una trama in nero lucido che dona un effetto davvero particolare sia alle cuffie che al case stesso.L'indossabilit√† invece √® un punto a mio parere un po incognita, perch√® io personalmente le trovo COMODISSIME nonostante la grandezza, non pesano e si incastrano all'orecchio alla perfezione, di contro per√≤ io cerco sempre di far indossare le cuffie anche ad amici e parenti, cos√¨ da avere un feedback anche da altre persone, e in questo caso ho avuto molti pareri discordanti, tra chi non riusciva nemmeno a inserirle per la dimensione, a chi come me le trovava comodissime, quindi consiglio personale, se siete persone che hanno un orecchio molto piccolo lasciate perdere queste cuffie perch√® anche con il gommino pi√π piccolo tenderanno a cadere.Passando invece al comparto audio abbiamo la vera e propria magia, audio PAZZESCO gi√† in configurazione standard abbiamo una qualit√† audio incredibile con un equalizzazione neutra e bassi medi e alti bilanciatissimi tra loro, bassi davvero profondi e corposi ma non troppo cupi da dare fastidio e un suono complessivo degno del marchio Yamaha, davvero approvatissimo il suono.Tramite l'app inoltre √® possibile anche andare a configurare pi√π finemente tutta l'equalizzazione delle cuffie per avere un audio personalizzato e di alta qualit√†.La cancellazione attiva del rumore funziona molto bene, ho provato altre cuffie di fascia alta e sono tutte pi√π o meno con lo stesso tipo di cancellazione, quindi da questo punto di vista anche altissima qualit√† ma niente di pi√π rispetto ad altre cuffie sulla stessa fascia di prezzo.Il case di ricarica come detto in precedenza √® molto ingombrante, ma comunque portatile ovviamente e comodo da tenere in borsa, un po meno in tasca, inoltre grazie alla sua ingente dimensione abbiamo una notevole batteria che ci permetter√† di utilizzare le cuffie fino a 22 ore di autonomia totale (6 ore + 16 ore) nella custodia di ricarica.In conclusione che dire di queste TW-E7B se non che sono delle cuffie bluetooth con la "C" maiuscola, hanno davvero tutto quello che si pu√≤ desiderare in un paio di cuffie e tutto estremamente al top! impermeabilit√†, cancellazione del rumore, compatibilit√† con assistenti vocali e app dedicata, suono eccezionale e un indossabilit√† "particolare" che forse posso considerare un punto di svantaggio perch√® diventa un prodotto che non tutti possono indossare correttamente date le sue dimensioni, ma oltre a questo neo e al prezzo sono delle cuffie a dir poco SUBLIMI.Spero di essere stato utile.

ReviewText: Yamaha ha recentemente lanciato una nuovissima gamma di cuffie true wireless, con le TW-E7B come protagoniste indiscusse.Tirandole fuori dalla scatola, sono rimasto sorpreso da quanto sia grossa la custodia che fa anche da batteria.Anche le cuffie stesse sono piuttosto grosse, infatti ero scettico sulla vestibilit√† e la comodit√† di questo paio di cuffie ma, tutto sommato, sono rimasto piacevolmente sorpreso. Nonostante l'ingombro non sono fastidiose e le ho indossate a lungo senza fastidi. Rimangono comunque molto sporgenti e a mio avviso non per tutte le orecchie, chi le ha piccole per me far√† fatica a indossarle.La canzone che uso per testare tutte le cuffie √® "Stratus" di Billy Cobham, perch√© ha un buon mix di frequenze e un dettaglio nel secondo pre-ritornello che sembra "esistere" solo nelle cuffie pi√π premium e valide.La definizione dei colpi di batteri √® chiara e il suono dei piatti √® brillante, anche se gli strumenti a corda sono un po' pi√π in sottofondo di quanto sono abituato a sentire con ad esempio le Bose Quietcomfort Earbuds 2.La cancellazione del rumore √® dove queste cuffie brillano davvero.  Anche se non sono andato in luoghi molto rumorosi come aerei o treni con loro, le ho indossate durante la mia giornata tipo. Non riescono a eliminare del tutto i rumori esterni "casuali" come un cane che abbaia di colpo, ma a malapena riuscivo a sentire il segnale acustico del mio microonde o della mia cappa standoci di fronte.La modalit√† "trasparenza" invece l'ho apprezzata molto, √® pi√π un amplificazione forzata delle voci attorno a noi.In conclusione, forse non le comprerei per essere le mie cuffie principali, poich√© penso che ci siano true wireless migliori e pi√π comodi su questa fascia di prezzo.  Tuttavia, se cercassi delle true wireless in-ear di cui la cancellazione del rumore fosse la principale funzione accompagnata da un sound di buon livello, le prenderei al 100%.

ReviewText: Gli auricolari Yamaha sono un prodotto di alta qualit√† che offre un'esperienza d'ascolto eccezionale. La loro tecnologia ANC avanzata elimina con precisione il rumore esterno, offrendo un audio estremamente nitido e inalterato. Inoltre, il suono cambia a seconda della forma dell'orecchio e di come gli auricolari vengono indossati.Gli auricolari Yamaha sono anche progettati per offrire un suono pieno e soddisfacente in qualsiasi ambiente. Il Listening Care Advanced regola le frequenze in base ai contenuti e all'ambiente, il che significa che puoi ascoltare la musica a qualsiasi volume senza perdere qualit√†.Inoltre, gli auricolari sono facilmente gestibili e personalizzabili tramite l'app Headphone Control. Le funzioni come la riproduzione, la pausa e il volume sono facilmente fruibili tramite gli auricolari stessi.Gli auricolari TW-E7B sono corredati da una custodia di ricarica e gommini extra di diverse misure. La custodia di ricarica √® molto pratica, poich√© permette di ricaricare gli auricolari fino a tre volte, estendendo cos√¨ l'autonomia fino a 22 ore. Inoltre, √® incluso anche il cavo di ricarica USB-C.In definitiva, gli auricolari Yamaha TW-E7B sono un'ottima scelta per chi cerca un suono e una cancellazione attiva del rumore di alta qualit√†. Tuttavia, l'indossabilit√† risulta po' scomoda e il prezzo potrebbe essere pi√π basso.

Product: HUAWEI FreeBuds SE 2 Wireless Headphones, White, Bluetooth, Up to 40 Hours Battery Life, Lightweight and Comfortable, Balanced Sound, AU Version
ReviewText: Amazing sound quality, very convenient and robust touch features, and impressive noise cancelling and ambient sound modes.I had been concerned about purchasing this item based on a number of negative reviews related to the noise cancelling and sound quality, but I now understand that such reviews are most likely from ocd types with a superficial grasp on the topics of signal processing and electronic hardware.If you want absolute isolation to outside noise interference, opt for industrial grade ear plugs; noise cancellation is not a magic panacea.Moreover, for the physical size and price of these earbuds, the sound quality is quite impressive. You'd likely require in excess of several thousands of dollars for custom headphones if you're looking for studio quality sound.

Product: HUAWEI FreeBuds SE 2 Wireless Headphones, White, Bluetooth, Up to 40 Hours Battery Life, Lightweight and Comfortable, Balanced Sound, AU Version

Product: HUAWEI FreeBuds SE 2 Wireless Headphones, White, Bluetooth, Up to 40 Hours Battery Life, Lightweight and Comfortable, Balanced Sound, AU Version
ReviewText: I previously had the Sony XM4 earbuds, but I returned them after finding the controls were inconsistent, pairing missed some of the time, and they were uncomfortable.The Galaxy Buds seem to have solved all of these. They pair easily with my phone (also a Samsung), the touch controls are reliable and responsive. I especially love the ability to long-press one earbud to open and play Spotify, this removes the "insert earbuds, get phone from pocket, unlock phone, start Spotify, put phone back" dance.They're also very comfortable. I have big, sitcky-out ears and these are smaller and fit much more nicely than the Sony ones. Wearing them for several hours is fine.One area where the Sony ones win is noise canceling. The Galaxy Bud 2 Pros are pretty good, but the Sonys were better. If you want distraction-free listening, these are good enough. If you need to he absolutely cocooned with your music to the exclusion of everything else, these might not meet your needs.

ReviewText: So I'm a music fan, and I've tried many different headphones and buds over the years.  My last pair were the Jabra Elite 7, which is fantastic, I've since lost them, and the lack of a find me feature is a pain.  So I bought the Samsung Buds. Product: Samsung EO-EG920BW White Genuine Headset/Handsfree/Headphone/Earphone with Volume Control for Galaxy Phones (Non Retail Packaging - Bulk Packaging)
ReviewText: I purchased the Anker Soundcore Life P3  for some long flights I was about to do, and I wanted the noise-canceling features, they performed amazingly well. I have used them for both movies and music, and the base is better than any earbuds I have used. The touch functions on the sides weren't great, and a bit slow, but to be honest I tend to use the device for stop-pause volume, etc. anyway. The app has multiple noise-canceling settings that work well with a sleep mode that allows you to add wind sea, birds, etc to help you sleep (very cool, I have Bose earbuds with this feature that cost 10x more) The Bluetooth has a very long range and all in all I give these 9 out of 10, I was gifted Beats earbuds for the flight and preferred the Anker Soundcore Life P3 for sound quality and features. They lose one point, not because of the earbuds themselves but because some flights wouldn't allow you to wear earbuds during landing, so I could watch the end of Marvels :(  Very happy.

Product: Samsung EO-EG920BW White Genuine Headset/Handsfree/Headphone/Earphone with Volume Control for Galaxy Phones (Non Retail Packaging - Bulk Packaging)
ReviewText: Only received these yesterday. So impressed. Connection to my iPhone, iPad and Apple TV was instant. With three different pairs of Apple AirPods, the devices search forever and sometimes still can‚Äôt find the AirPods  without a device reset. Noise cancelling is brilliant. The buds fit comfortably in the ear and don‚Äôt feel like they will fall out. Haven‚Äôt tested the battery life fully yet, but used them to watch movies for five hours without a problem. I was able to leave the room where they were connected to the Apple TV and still hear the sound at the other end of the house. Overall, just in the short time I‚Äôve used the buds, they are brilliant. I got a discount price, but they are worth paying the full price if not discounted. I don‚Äôt write many reviews, but these earbuds are so impressive, I felt I should give my opinion to others who are trying to decide whether to purchase.

ReviewText: I bought these headphone/earbuds for listening to mainly classical & baroque music. All registers, low, mid's and high's sound powerful and clear.  The only other caveat is you'll need a good MP3 player.  I'm using a Surfans brand player which has an adjustable EQ band.  Sound cancellation of exterior noise is good, as the earbuds do an adequate job of fitting in the ear canal and blocking out most noise.  For the price, an unbeatable bargain.

ReviewText: A customer of mine recommended these headphones so I decided to give them a whirl. Love the design of these, and the way the earbuds are made from wood, it gives them a classy look that stands out from traditional earbuds. I like the cord as well, it does get twisted up from time to time but definitely doesn't tangle like regular earbuds. I've compared these to regular Apple earbuds that come with iPhones, as well as the AKG's that Samsung provides in the boxes that come with the S8 series and Note 8 and in my opinion they are superior. It's noticeable over the iPhone earbuds, and with the AKG's it provides a more solid base without being overbearing. I have small ears so the attachment that came with these earbuds was a good snug fit, but they also provide other attachments in case you want a different fit. It's important with these that you insert them deep enough into the ear to hear the thump of the base, you'll know if they're not in correctly. As far as noice cancellation these are fantastic...I had people talking to me when I first tried them out that were standing bedside me speaking at normal volume and I couldn't hear a thing. It's been about a month since I've owned these and I say they're worth every penny üòé

ReviewText: I read good things about these in audiophile forums and wasn't disappointed.They have surprisingly good clarity, resolution and instrument separation for the price.Their sound is on the bright side of things, but not fatiguing. It's a shade brighter than neutral. There can be the occasional sharp spike in the high-mids, but not bothersome.But it depends on the person's taste. If you like a warm/dark sounding IEM then these are probably not for you.The bass is tight and lean, it's not woofy or artificial. If you're a bass head then it's probably not going to be enough for you, but if you like "accurate" bass then you will like these. The rumble is there, but it takes more of a supportive role than a primary role.The soundstage is accurate. Not overly wide, not overly narrow. You get the punch in the middle while getting a good amount of width. The imaging is good, I can easily pick out where each instrument is coming from.The comfort okay, not bad, not great. I can't wear them for more than 1.5 hrs before I start to wanna take them off. But I've got stiff cartilage in my ears which makes them sensitive to pressure over time, so most ppl should be fine.They are more comfy than my previous Bluetooth IEMs though.I don't love the look of the cable but it's not a deal breaker. Seems to sound good.Build quality is great with the all metal shells. I have no fear of them breaking in my pocket.I'm surprised they are this cheap, they're really good. Don't get me wrong, they're not gonna wow you as much as some great headphones, but their Amazon rating should be higher than 4.4. I bought some Bluetooth earphones for around the same price a few years ago and these are twice as good. These are underrated.Easy to drive too. I have them playing through my phone.

ReviewText: This is my second budget IEM after the Salnotes 7hz Zero. With these you get a substantial improvement in build quality for that single step up the price ladder, with a nice metal shell that I find very comfortable to wear for prolonged periods (I find I enjoy putting them in when they're cold!) and decent quality braided cable. A lot has been written about how these sound, I'd just reiterate that they're on the brighter side than I'm used to, but not at all tiring, there is a richness and clarity with technical detail and a tight and precise bass response that I enjoy. This IEM journey has been a cautious one for me, I'm not ready to spend the sort of money I would on some decent open back headphones. But the Simgot EW200s represent excellent value for money in my opinion.

ReviewText: I watched a lot of reviews and many people have been hyping these IEMs up with positive reviews. Gaming wise I feel like it's better if you get another IEM as the soundstage is not too wide in my opinion, so intricate sounds like footsteps is harder to pinpoint the exact direction. For the price, I thought it's a really good purchase for a daily earphone.

ReviewText: Zuerst das Negative:Der Frequenzgang gef√§llt mir pers√∂hnlich nicht sonderlich, ich w√ºrde ihn aber nicht schlecht nennen, viele m√∂gen das so. Dadurch, dass es keine krassen peaks oder dips gibt, ist er auch sehr einfach mit EQ zu ver√§ndern. In meinen Ohren sitzen die IEMs leider nicht sehr komfortabel, das wird aber wieder von der Person abh√§ngen.  Was mir negativ am Klang aufgefallen ist, ist, dass er nicht sonderlich nat√ºrlich klingt und es sich manchmal so anh√∂rt, als w√ºrden die Instrumente nicht richtig zusammen funktionieren. Er klingt generell sehr trocken und weniger "abgeschlossen", was glaube ich mit der Geschwindigkeit des verwendeten Treibers zusammen h√§ngt.  Die Stimme ist meistens nicht sonderlich fokussiert, sondern steht eher im ganzen Raum, wovon ich kein Fan bin.Damit sind wir beim Positiven: Der IEM ist enorm hochaufl√∂send. So, wie ich es noch nie bei einem IEM geh√∂rt habe, inklusive vielen, die bis zu dem Zehnfachen kosten. Immer wenn ich mit anderen IEMs K√ºnstler wie Bob Dylan oder Faber h√∂re, habe ich das Gef√ºhl die Textur auf der Stimme komme nicht richtig r√ºber, wenn man es mit einem HD600 vergleicht. Das ist nat√ºrlich nicht fair, und ich sage nicht, dass der ew200 ganz da ist, aber ich habe zumindest nie das Gef√ºhl, dass ich etwas verpasse. Die Klarheit und Seperation der einzelnen Details ist auch wirklich enorm gut. Ich habe gestern eine Vorlesung mit dem HD600 geguckt und dann zu dem ew200 gewechselt und mir ist sofort ein ganz eindeutiger Hall im Raum aufgefallen, den ich vorher nicht geh√∂rt hatte. Der Bass ist ohne EQ sehr laut, ich habe ihn 7db runtergestellt, was theoretisch deutlich niedriger ist, als ich normalerweise h√∂re, aber der "punch" ist so gut, dass mir das garnicht so vorkommt. Im vergleich zu etwas wie dem 7hz Timeless ist das wirklich Tag und Nacht. Da ist der Bass noch lauter, aber es gibt garkeinen richtigen impact. Sachen wie die Textur auf der Stimme kommen da auch so gut wie garnicht r√ºber. Generell ist Einzige, was der Timeless besser macht das aufger√§umt sein und die Koh√§renz des Klangs. K√∂nnte ich nur einen behalten, w√ºrde ich auf jeden Fall diesen nehmen. Wenn ihr von etwas, wie einem Truthear Hola kommt, ist die Aufl√∂sung eine komplett andere Welt, ich k√∂nnte mir sogar vorstellen, dass sie am Anfang √ºberfordert.

ReviewText: I am very picky when it comes to sound quality. It is astonishing you can get something that sounds this amazing for $39Up until now I have avoided IEM because of fitment issues. These are a nice size and quite comfortable. The silicone tips that came with them are not for me. I ordered a variety pack of foam tips and the large ones were just the ticket. I struggled until that point getting a good seal, and was somewhat disappointed with the low end. Once the proper tips for me were put on, now the seal is tight and sounds perfect on the bottom end.If you like a nice clean open sound, with crystal clear mids and highs, with a generally solid bottom end, these are great. The sub frequencies are present and accounted for, just don't slam like some people like.These are exceptionally easy to drive so no extra stuff is needed. a simple usb c dongle is fine.

ReviewText: La philips e' sempre una garanzia. Io compro spesso cuffie e auricolari di questa marca e mi trovo sempre bene. Queste per la palestra nello specifico le avevo gia' comprate una volta lo scorso anno, poi utilizzandole parecchio si sono rotte (funzionavano ancora ma si erano staccati dei pezzi) e quindi le ho ricomprate. Le ho appena aperte e per adesso sono soddisfatta: consegna veloce e nei tempi, imballaggio integro e auricolari funzionanti.
